p: Lineweaver–Burk plots and secondary plots showed that MO5 and MO9 competitively and non-competitively, respectively, inhibited AChE ( Figure 5(A,C)) with K i values of 2.52 ± 0.17 and 7.04 ± 0.32 µM, respectively ( Figure 5(B,D)), which suggest that MO5 is a potent, selective and competitive inhibitor of AChE that binds to the active site of AChE, and that MO9 binds to a site other than the active site of AChE and changes the 3D structure of the enzyme, thus inhibiting enzyme activity.
